Ah, now I see `@otovo/shared`! In this case, we should keep all the tsconfig files. Here's how I would set up the `@otovo/shared/tsconfig.json` specifically, since it's a shared package that the Next.js apps depend on:

```json
// @otovo/shared/tsconfig.json
{
  "extends": "../../tsconfig.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "outDir": "./dist",
    "rootDir": ".",
    "composite": true,
    "declaration": true,
    "declarationMap": true,
    "jsx": "react-jsx",
    "baseUrl": ".",
  },
  "include": [
    "*.tsx",
    "*.ts",
    "*.js",
    "*.jsx"
  ],
  "exclude": ["node_modules", "dist"]
}
```

And make sure your Next.js apps' tsconfig files include a reference to the shared package in their paths:

```json
// breeze/tsconfig.json (and similar for my-page and storefront)
{
  "extends": "../tsconfig.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "plugins": [{ "name": "next" }],
    "allowJs": true,
    "noEmit": true,
    "incremental": true,
    "baseUrl": ".",
    "paths": {
      "@otovo/shared": ["../@otovo/shared"]
    }
  },
  "include": ["next-env.d.ts", "**/*.ts", "**/*.tsx", ".next/types/**/*.ts"],
  "exclude": ["node_modules"]
}
```

This setup:
1. Allows `@otovo/shared` to be built independently
2. Enables proper type generation for the shared components
3. Makes the shared components and their types available to the Next.js apps
4. Maintains the existing Next.js configuration
