how could I safely access monthly_leasing_gross_price withouth getting a headache all over my code-base?
There are several ways to safely handle this optional property that's conditional on the purchase model. Here's my recommended approach using discriminated unions:

```typescript
type Cloud$FinancingOptionGroupBase = {
  product_category: 'pv' | 'battery' | 'ev_charger' | 'heat_pump' | 'other';
  total_gross_price: number;
  total_gross_price_unmodified: number;
  discounts: Array<Cloud$ShoppingCartDiscount>;
};

type Cloud$BuyNowOption = Cloud$FinancingOptionGroupBase & {
  purchase_model_code: Cloud$PurchaseModelCodeBuyNow;
};

type Cloud$LoanOption = Cloud$FinancingOptionGroupBase & {
  purchase_model_code: Cloud$PurchaseModelCodeLoan;
};

type Cloud$LeasingOption = Cloud$FinancingOptionGroupBase & {
  purchase_model_code: Cloud$PurchaseModelCodeLeasing;
  monthly_leasing_gross_price: number; // Required for leasing
};

type Cloud$FinancingOptionGroup = 
  | Cloud$BuyNowOption 
  | Cloud$LoanOption 
  | Cloud$LeasingOption;
```

Now you can safely access it using type narrowing:

```typescript
function handleFinancing(option: Cloud$FinancingOptionGroup) {
  if (option.purchase_model_code === 'LEASING') {
    // TypeScript knows monthly_leasing_gross_price exists here
    return option.monthly_leasing_gross_price;
  }
  // Handle other cases...
}
```

Or create a type guard:

```typescript
function isLeasingOption(option: Cloud$FinancingOptionGroup): option is Cloud$LeasingOption {
  return option.purchase_model_code === 'LEASING';
}

// Usage:
if (isLeasingOption(option)) {
  // TypeScript knows monthly_leasing_gross_price exists here
  console.log(option.monthly_leasing_gross_price);
}
```

This approach:
1. Makes the types more precise
2. Eliminates optional properties
3. Provides better TypeScript inference
4. Makes it impossible to make mistakes with the leasing price
5. Gives you compile-time safety

